# {{.ProjectName}} — Agent Operating Manual

This is the loop. Every Claude session (and every human contributor) follows
it. The goal is **make progress with no ceremony, leave the workspace better
than you found it, and never break anything you wouldn't want to defend in
review.**

If you only read one thing, read **§1 (Resume) → §3 (Work) → §6 (Update
status)**. The rest is reference.

---

## §0 — The 30-second mental model

- Work lives in `.squad/items/`. One markdown file per item. Frontmatter +
  body. The frontmatter is greppable.
- Done items move to `.squad/done/`, keeping `.squad/items/` as the active
  queue.
- Quick board: `.squad/STATUS.md` — what's in flight, what's ready, what's
  blocked. The board is a convenience pointer; the items themselves are the
  contract.
- Operational state (claims, chat, file touches) lives in
  `~/.squad/global.db`. That database is machine-local; your items are
  shared via git.
- Implementation plans (per-feature design docs) belong in `docs/plans/`
  which should be gitignored — those are ephemeral working notes, not
  durable.

---

## §1 — Resume (start of session)

Tier the resume by the item you're about to pick up. Most sessions pick a
≤1h fix off the top of the Ready stack; full-tier reading on every one of
those is overhead that doesn't change your approach.

**Fast tier — ≤1h items:**

1. `squad register --as "agent-$(openssl rand -hex 2)" --name "agent-XXXX" && squad tick`
   — register with a fresh unique ID so parallel sessions don't collide.
   The `--as` value persists per session (keyed on TERM_SESSION_ID /
   TMUX_PANE / SQUAD_SESSION_ID), so two Claude Code sessions in one
   worktree each keep their own identity. Always register-and-tick in one
   shell invocation.
2. `.squad/STATUS.md` — just the In-Progress line + the relevant Ready row.
3. `.squad/items/<ID>-*.md` — the item you're taking; the contract is in
   its `## Acceptance criteria`.

The item is self-contained for small fixes. Skip vision/roadmap docs unless
something in the item points you there.

**Full tier — use when** the session is cold (first pickup of the day),
the item is ≥1d, the item touches an architectural bet, or you'll be making
judgment calls the roadmap should inform. Then read your project's
`CLAUDE.md`, `docs/VISION.md`, `docs/ROADMAP.md`, and this file in full.

Then explicitly pick an item — don't silently start coding. Announce it.

---

## §2 — Pick an item

Sources of work, in priority order:

1. **In-progress items** in `.squad/items/` with `status: in_progress`.
   Continue these first — abandoned in-flight work rots fastest.
2. **Blocked items** that may now be unblocked. Check `blocked-by` for
   resolved deps.
3. **Ready items** with the highest priority (P0 → P3) and lowest estimate
   within priority. Prefer 1h–1d items in a single session; spawn parallel
   agents for 3d+ items.
4. **User asks** — if the user names a thing, do that, but file it as an
   item before starting if it's >1h.

Atomic claim via CLI:

```bash
squad claim <ID> --intent "one sentence" [--touches path1,path2]
```

If exit 1, the item is already claimed — pick another. The DB is the live
lock. The item file's `status: in_progress` gets written at §6 close-out,
not now — avoids merge conflicts across parallel worktrees.

When you pick:

- **Pre-flight blocker check:** verify the item's `blocked-by:` list is
  empty OR every blocker has `status: done`. If a blocker is still open,
  pick a different item.
- **Pre-flight repo check:** if any `references:` path resolves outside the
  current repo, skip the item and pick the next. Cross-repo work gets done
  in its own session.
- Announce in chat: *"Picking up <ID>: <title>."*

