## §12 — Anti-patterns (don't do these)

- **Don't run `--no-verify` on commits.** Pre-commit hooks exist for a
  reason; if it's failing, fix the cause.
- **Don't claim "done" without running tests.**
- **Don't ship code you wouldn't defend in review.** §4.5 is the bar.
- **Don't skip TDD silently.**
- **Don't skip code review.** §4.7 is mandatory.
- **Don't perform-agree with the reviewer.** Verify findings; push back
  with evidence when wrong.
- **Don't write planning markdown into the codebase.** Use `.squad/items/`
  for tracked work; `docs/plans/` (gitignored) for ephemeral plans.
- **Don't add comments that explain what the change is for.** The commit
  message holds that.
- **Don't open more than one in-progress item per session unless using
  parallel agents.**
- **Don't dispatch parallel agents on related work.** They will conflict.
- **Don't write new docs by default.** Items are the durable docs.
- **Don't extend a time-box silently.**
- **Don't ship without an evidence paste.**
- **Don't `claim` without ticking first.**
- **Don't `commit` without a pre-commit tick.**
- **Don't go silent on a long claim.** Quiet agents surprise the team.
- **Don't @-mention to shout.** A mention is "I need THIS agent"; a plain
  message is "posting for transparency."
- **Don't release a claim just because you paused for lunch.** Heartbeat
  handles absence. Release when handing off or done.

